value.value: anomaly in the rates of airflow during forced vital capacity determination

definition.value: Do not confuse with forced expiratory volume, a test of pulmonary ventilation.

value.value: anomaly in the volume of air contained in the lungs at the end of maximal inspiration
anomaly in the volume of air remaining in the lungs at the end of a normal expiration
anomaly in the volume of air remaining in the lungs at the end of maximal expiration
anomaly in the amount of air that is exhaled by a maximal expiration following a maximal inspiration
less likely than normal to develop hepatic steatosis
anomaly in the maximal volume of air that can be inspired after the end of a normal expiration
anomaly in the extra volume of air that can be inspired with maximal effort after reaching the end of a normal inspiration
anomaly in the volume of air inspired or expired during each normal respiratory cycle
anomaly in the action of the lungs, diaphragm, ribs and chest wall during respiration
absence or almost complete absence of oxygen from inspired gases, in blood or tissues
elevated concentration of CO2 in the blood, alveoli or other tissues resulting in the increased pressure of this component of body gases
elevated concentration of O2 in the blood, alveoli or other tissues resulting in the increased pressure of this component of body gases
a state in which there is a increased amount of air entering the pulmonary alveoli (increased alveolar ventilation), which causes an decrease in arterial carbon dioxide level
a state in which there is a reduced amount of air entering the pulmonary alveoli (decreased alveolar ventilation), which causes an increase in arterial carbon dioxide level
anomaly in the process of gas exchange
less likely than normal to develop abnormally high levels of circulating lipids

any structural anomaly of the membrane between the capillary blood and alveolar air, comprised of the alveolar epithelium and the capillary epithelium and their adherent basement membranes and epithelial cell cytoplasm
anomaly in the amount of gas taken up by pulmonary capillary blood per minute per unit of average oxygen pressure gradient between alveolar gas and pulmonary capillary blood
anomaly in the ratio of alveolar ventilation to simultaneous capillary blood flow in the lung

definition.value: Changes in the ventilation-perfusion ratio alter the amount of O2 or CO2 in the blood.

value.value: anomaly in any measure of the processes involved in respiration
anomaly in the opposition to flow of air caused by the forces of friction, measured as the ratio of driving pressure to the rate of air flow
anomaly in the amount of oxygen and carbon dioxide in the blood
anomaly in the results of measures of responsiveness to allergens, pharmacological solutions, or control solutions
improved or impaired performance during controlled physical activity
anomaly in the ability of the lung to distend in response to pressure without disruption, usually expressed as the unit volume of change in the lung per unit of pressure

definition.value: This is a measure of the stiffness of the lung and indicative for diseases that cause fibrosis or edema in the lungs.

value.value: anomalous response in bronchial provocation tests
less easily provoked into bronchoconstriction during bronchial provocation testing
anomaly in the exchange of oxygen and carbon dioxide between the alveolar air and pulmonary capillary blood
anomaly in the measurements gathered in a chamber that encloses the body and in which changes in volume are recorded

anomaly of the respiratory minute volume, or the total volume of gas per minute inspired or expired expressed in liters per minute; refers to the exchange of air between the total respiratory space and the environment

definition.value: Do not confuse with pulmonary ventilation rate (aka respiratory rate). Pulmonary ventilation is the volume of air per minute; pulmonary ventilation rate is the number of breaths per minute.

value.value: any structural anomaly of the oval or bean shaped bodies located along the lymphatic system that consist of densely packed lymphocytes, lymph fluid and connective tissue, and is the site where acquired immune responses are launched
any structural anomaly of the lymph nodes located around the axillary vein that receive lymphatic drainage from the upper or forelimb, scapular region and pectoral region
any structural anomaly of the membranous processes on the internal surface of the lymph node capsule, consisting of connective tissue and muscle fibers
any structural anomaly in the outer area of the lymph node that has B and T cell domains

label.value: abnormal lymph node B cell domain morphology

value.value: any structural anomaly of the part of the lymph node cortex in which B lymphocytes home to primary follicles to survey follicular dendritic cells (FDCs); antigen stimulated B cells proliferate and differentiate within the follicles forming distinctive germinal centers

label.value: abnormal lymph node primary follicle morphology

value.value: any structural anomaly of an unstimulated network of follicular dendritic cells and small resting B cells in the lymph node cortex

definition.value: Cells in the primary follicle consist of cohesive aggregates of small, normal-appearing lymphocytes.

label.value: abnormal lymph node secondary follicle morphology

value.value: any structural anomaly of a lymph node primary follicle that has undergone antigenic challenge and is characterized by a ring of concentrically packed B lymphocytes surrounding a germinal center, which contains proliferating B cells, and a mantle area that contains nondividing B cells and some helper T cells with macrophages and follicular dendritic cells interspersed

label.value: abnormal lymph node T cell domain morphology

value.value: any structural anomaly of the paracortex and interfollicular cortex of the lymph node in which T lymphocytes home to survey dendritic cells; T lymphocytes proliferate in the paracortex and enlarge it but do not produce structures analogous to germinal centers
any structural anomaly in the area of the lymph node through which lymph leaves the node; it contains macrophages and antibody-secreting plasma cells
any structural anomaly in the lymphatic tubes entering the lymph node
any structural anomaly in the lymphatic tube exiting the lymph node
any structural anomaly of the lymph nodes found near the neck and shoulders
any structural anomaly of the lymph nodes which drain the legs
any structural anomaly of the lymph nodes located in the groin area
any structural anomaly of one of the branches of the splenic artery

any structural anomaly of the parenchymatous tissue network of the spleen that consists of loose plates or cords (sinuses) infiltrated with red blood cells where most of the blood filtration occurs and degenerate erythrocytes are removed from the circulation

any structural anomaly of the parenchymatous tissue of the spleen that surrounds splenic blood vessels, consists of compact masses of lymphatic cells and is where foreign material removed from the blood is used to initiate an immune reaction that results in the production of antibodies

definition.value: Note that there is no consensus in the literature about which compartments constitute the white pulp or the ramifications of the microvasculature. In addition, notable differences exist between humans and rodents. In this ontology, the marginal sinus and marginal zone have been included as part of the white pulp.

label.value: abnormal spleen periarteriolar lymphoid sheath morphology

value.value: any structural anomaly of the area of the spleen in which T cells surround the central arteriole
any structural anomaly of the area of the spleen secondary B follicle where rapid B-cell proliferation, somatic hypermutation, and selection for antigen binding occurs

definition.value: Germinal centers are often identified by the binding of peanut agglutinin (PNA).
